thread.title: Red Wings vs. Maple Leafs: Babcock back in Detroit, on visitors side
thread.title_full: Red Wings vs. Maple Leafs: Babcock back in Detroit, on visitors side

author: freep.com
title: Red Wings vs. Maple Leafs: Babcock back in Detroit, on visitors side
text:
MORE On one point everyone agrees: Mike Babcock oozes intensity.
Those closer to him, such as new Detroit Red Wings coach Jeff Blashill, hint there is a relaxed version of Babcock. His former players never saw it.
Babcock returns to Joe Louis Arena on Friday to stand, for the first time, behind the visitors bench as head coach of the Toronto Maple Leafs. He will do so again a week later, when the Wings host the Leafs in the season opener. Whether or not next Friday there will be some kind of sign welcoming back the man who spent the last decade coaching the Wings has been debated within the organization — one side wanting to acknowledge Babcock's long tenure in Detroit, the other adamant that a guy who wanted to leave and who is now coaching a division rival should not receive special treatment.
That is not within the players' purview. To them, he is remembered as demanding, helpful, hurtful if allowed.
"He was a big part of some of our careers," captain Henrik Zetterberg said. "The first five (years) we had a lot of success. We went deep into the post season. '08 was the most fun season. The preparation — that was the biggest difference, just every day, practice and before games, the level of preparation. You knew game plan before every game. You knew players. That was a step up from what I was used to before.
"He is a competitive guy. I always come back to the preparation, the amount of time he spent on hockey. He spent a lot of time here at the rink, but I don't think the off switch was off when he left the rink."
Babcock coached the Wings from 2005-2015. The last season had its turbulence. Babcock seemed to signal he wanted to go elsewhere when he said an extension would not be negotiated during the season, yet he also said on opening night he didn't think it was his last year in Detroit. The Wings made offer after offer, and hence the bitterness from some within the organization, because shortly after the playoffs ended, Babcock asked for permission to talk to suitors before the June 30 expiration of his contract. The Wings made the best of the situation, having interested teams sign an agreement to give the Wings a third-round draft pick upon hiring Babcock.
The Maple Leafs topped the Sabres at the 11th hour, wooing Babcock with $50 million over eight years. This was not greeted with sadness within the Wings dressing room, especially after a first-round loss that left the Wings having won one playoff round the last four years.
"I think it was time for us to get a new voice in the locker room," Johan Franzen said, "and maybe it was time for him, too, to try something else. It is a good atmosphere in there. We are happy to have Blash coaching us."
The Wings turned to Blashill, who had spent one season with Babcock in Detroit and three years talking to him regularly while coaching in Grand Rapids.
"We were on the phone a couple times a week. I was able to go through playoff runs where unfortunately they were done but he was able to follow us and help me through some of that process," Blashill said. "So the amount I learned was an exponential amount. Very good friendship and ton of respect as a coach."
Asked about Babcock's intensity, Blashill smiled.
"At the NHL draft, we always kind of kick back and have a good time," Blashill said. "I think his wife would joke that there is 'Summer Mike' and 'Winter Mike' and they are just different. But he has a great intensity to him and a great focus to him and I appreciate all those things."
Younger players sometimes struggled to do so.
"He is an intense guy for sure. He is an intense coach," Gustav Nyquist said. "He is hard on you, especially the younger guys. But I think he wants to help you, so you know as a young guy you have got to be able to take it the right way. Some days he is going to be harder on you than others but you know his goal is to make you better."
That was made clear, one intense day after another.
